<h1>From Nicholas Cooke</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Providence January 1st 1776</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>Upon Receipt of your Excellencys Letter of the 23d ulto<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0002-fn-0001" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0002-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> I employed Two Persons to apply to the Housekeepers in this Town individually for Blankets for the Army. They have collected about 180 which will be sent forward this Day. It is full as large a Number as I expected to procure considering how we have been exhausted by Supplies to various Parts of the Service. I shall immediately take Measures for collecting more from the Country Towns.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0002-fn-0002" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0002-fn-0002-ptr">2</a></p>
<p>I refer your Excellency to General Lee for the Particulars of his Expedition to Rhode Island; which I hope will be attended with beneficial Consequences to the Colony.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0002-fn-0003" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0002-fn-0003-ptr">3</a></p>
<p>I received yours upon the Subject of reinlisting the Army,<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0002-fn-0004" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0002-fn-0004-ptr">4</a> but from the distressed State of the Colony, and the Multiplicity of Business pressing me was incapable of giving you a satisfactory Answer. Nor can I at present do any thing more than renew
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-03-02-pb-0006">[6]</span>
my Assurances of giving every Assistance in my Power to the Service. I am with great Truth and Esteem Sir Your most obedient and most humble Servant</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Nichls Cooke</p>
</div>
<div class="postscript">
<p>P.S. You will receive by Mr Coomer Hale who carries the Blankets, an Account of the Cost of them.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0002-fn-0005" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0002-fn-0005-ptr">5</a> I shall be obliged to your Excellency for giving Orders for the Payment of it to him. By the same Conveyance I send you a Box and a Basket left for your Excellency by Mr Penet, and the other French Gentleman who accompanied him.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0002-fn-0006" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0002-fn-0006-ptr">6</a></p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0002-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Letter Signed: a letter not in the authors handwriting, but signed by the author ]">LS</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0002-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0002-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0550" class="document">Circular to the New England Governments, 23 Dec. 1775</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0002-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0002-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0003" class="document">John Smith to GW, this date</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0002-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0002-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>Charles Lee left Cambridge for Rhode Island on 20 Dec. and returned ten days later. See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0536" class="document">Cooke to GW, 19 Dec.</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0560-0001" class="document">GW to Hancock, 25 Dec. 1775</a>. During his stay in the colony, Lee gave instructions for erecting several fortifications, and acting on his own authority, he compelled a number of Loyalists in Newport to take an oath not to give provisions or intelligence to the British forces and to take up arms for the American cause if called upon by the Continental Congress or the Rhode Island general assembly (<span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Pennsylvania Gazette</span> [Philadelphia], 17 Jan. 1775; <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Frank Moore. &lt;i&gt;Diary of the American Revolution from Newspapers and Original Documents&lt;/i&gt;. 2 vols. New York, 185960. ]">Moore, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Diary</span></span>, 18384. See also Nathanael Greene to Samuel Ward, Sr., 31 Dec. 1775, in <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Richard K. Showman et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;The Papers of General Nathanael Greene&lt;/i&gt;. 13 vols. Chapel Hill, N.C., 19762005. ]">Showman, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Greene Papers</span></span>, 1:17075, Stephen Moylan to Joseph Reed, 2 Jan. 1776, in <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ William B. Reed. &lt;i&gt;Life and Correspondence of Joseph Reed, Military Secretary of Washington, at Cambridge; Adjutant-General of the Continental Army; Member of the Congress of the United States; and President of the Executive Council of the State of Pennsylvania&lt;/i&gt;. 2 vols. Philadelphia, 1847. ]">Reed, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Joseph Reed</span></span>, 1:13740, and Charles Lee to Robert Morris, 3 Jan. 1776, in <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ [[Charles Lee]]. &lt;i&gt;The Lee Papers&lt;/i&gt;. 4 vols. New York, 1872-75. In &lt;i&gt;Collections of the New-York Historical Society&lt;/i&gt;, vols. 47. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Lee Papers</span></span>, 1:23334).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0002-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0002-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0443" class="document">Circular to the New England Governments, 5 Dec. 1775</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0002-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0002-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>This account has not been identified. See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0025" class="document">GW to Cooke, 6 Jan. 1776</a>. Coomer Hale has not been identified.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0002-fn-0006-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0002-fn-0006">6</a>

   <p>For the gifts of fruit, sugar, and liquors sent by Pierre Penet and Emmanuel de Pliarne, see their <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0530" class="document">letter to GW of 18 December</a>. The two men had gone to Philadelphia to propose to Congress a plan for importing arms and ammunition.</p>

</div>
</div>
